        <h1>SAE Question Bank 2078 - 2078</h1>
        <p><strong>Full Marks:</strong> 60 + 20 + 20</p>
        <p><strong>Pass Marks:</strong> 24 + 8 + 8</p>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> 3 hours</p>
    <h2>Section A: Attempt any TWO questions</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>What is ethical decision-making? What is the element that makes a good framework for an ethical decision? Explain the code of ethics in detail.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Ethical decision-making refers to the process of making decisions that are morally right and socially responsible. It involves considering the potential consequences of actions, identifying ethical principles and values, and weighing the interests of all stakeholders involved. Ethical decision-making requires a deliberate and conscious effort to choose a course of action that is consistent with one&#8217;s values and principles.</p>
<p>There are several elements that make a good framework for ethical decision-making, including:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Identifying the problem or dilemma:</strong></span></p>
<p>This involves understanding the situation and the potential ethical implications of different courses of action.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Identifying the ethical principles involved:</strong></span></p>
<p>This involves considering the values and principles that are relevant to the situation, such as honesty, fairness, and respect for others.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Seeking out all relevant information:</strong></span></p>
<p>This involves gathering as much information as possible about the situation and the potential consequences of different actions.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Considering the perspectives of all stakeholders:</strong></span></p>
<p>This involves considering the interests and perspectives of all stakeholders involved in the situation, including employees, customers, shareholders, and the wider community.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Weighing the consequences of different actions:</strong></span></p>
<p>This involves considering the potential consequences of different courses of action, both positive and negative.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>f) Making a decision and taking action:</strong></span></p>
<p>This involves making a decision based on the above considerations and taking action in a way that is consistent with one&#8217;s values and principles.</p>
<p>A code of ethics is a set of principles and values that guide the behavior of individuals and organizations. It typically outlines expectations for behavior, such as honesty, fairness, and respect for others, and provides guidance on how to handle ethical dilemmas and conflicts. A code of ethics can help to create a culture of ethical behavior within an organization and promote consistency in decision-making.</p>
<p>A code of ethics typically includes several key components, such as:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Core values:</strong> These are the fundamental principles and beliefs that guide ethical behavior, such as honesty, integrity, and respect for others.</li>
<li><strong>Standards of conduct:</strong> These are specific guidelines for behavior, such as guidelines for interacting with customers, handling confidential information, and avoiding conflicts of interest.</li>
<li><strong>Accountability and enforcement:</strong> This outlines how the code of ethics will be enforced, and what the consequences will be for violating the code.</li>
<li><strong>Training and communication:</strong> This outlines how the code of ethics will be communicated to employees and how they will be trained on the principles and values it contains.</li>
</ol>
<p>Overall, ethical decision-making is a critical component of responsible behavior in both personal and professional contexts. By understanding the key elements of ethical decision-making and following a code of ethics, individuals and organizations can create a culture of ethical behavior and promote positive outcomes for all stakeholders involved.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Define intellectual property ownership. How do you protect ownership right? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Intellectual property ownership refers to the legal right of individuals or organizations to own and control their original creations, such as inventions, literary and artistic works, designs, and symbols. Intellectual property rights are protected by law and provide exclusive rights to the owner, such as the right to use, license, sell, or prevent others from using their creations.</p>
<p>There are several ways to protect intellectual property ownership rights, including:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Patents</strong>: Patents protect inventions and give the owner exclusive rights to manufacture, use, and sell the invention for a set period of time.</li>
<li><strong>Copyrights</strong>: Copyrights protect original literary and artistic works, such as books, music, films, and software, and give the owner the exclusive right to reproduce, distribute, and display their work.</li>
<li><strong>Trademarks</strong>: Trademarks protect symbols, names, logos, and slogans that are used to identify and distinguish products or services, and give the owner exclusive rights to use and license their trademark.</li>
<li><strong>Trade secrets</strong>: Trade secrets protect confidential information that gives a business a competitive advantage, such as customer lists, manufacturing processes, and business plans.</li>
</ol>
<p>To protect intellectual property ownership rights, individuals and organizations can take several steps, such as:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Registering their creations with the appropriate government agency, such as the United States Patent and Trademark Office or the United States Copyright Office.</li>
<li>Using contracts and non-disclosure agreements to protect trade secrets and confidential information.</li>
<li>Monitoring the marketplace for unauthorized use of their intellectual property and taking legal action when necessary.</li>
<li>Educating employees, contractors, and partners on the importance of intellectual property rights and the consequences of infringement.</li>
</ol>
<p>Overall, protecting intellectual property ownership rights is essential for promoting innovation and creativity, and for ensuring that creators can benefit from their creations. By understanding the different forms of intellectual property and taking steps to protect them, individuals and organizations can safeguard their intellectual property rights and ensure that they receive the recognition and compensation they deserve.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Define the digital divide. Explain different enablers of the digital divide.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The digital divide refers to the gap between those who have access to and use of digital technologies and those who do not. It is a global issue that affects individuals, communities, and countries, and it has significant social, economic, and political implications.</p>
<p>There are several enablers of the digital divide, including:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Economic Factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Economic factors such as income, employment, and education level can contribute to the digital divide. Those with higher income and education levels may have greater access to digital technologies and the skills needed to use them effectively.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Geographic Factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Geographic factors such as location and infrastructure can contribute to the digital divide. Those living in rural or remote areas may have limited access to broadband internet and other digital technologies.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Demographic Factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Demographic factors such as age, race, and gender can contribute to the digital divide. Certain groups may face barriers to accessing digital technologies or may lack the skills and knowledge needed to use them effectively.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Technological Factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Technological factors such as the cost of devices and software can contribute to the digital divide. Those who cannot afford the latest technologies may be left behind, and those who lack the skills to use them may also be at a disadvantage.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Cultural Factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Cultural factors such as language and social norms can contribute to the digital divide. Those who speak languages other than English or who come from non-digital cultures may face barriers to accessing and using digital technologies.</p>
<p>Overall, the digital divide is a complex issue that is influenced by a range of factors. Addressing the digital divide will require a multi-faceted approach that considers the economic, geographic, demographic, technological, and cultural factors that contribute to it. By working to close the digital divide, we can create a more equitable and just society where everyone has equal access to digital technologies and the benefits they offer.</p>
</div>
<h2>Section B: Attempt any EIGHT questions</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the factor of social change?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Social change refers to the transformation of societal institutions, behaviors, attitudes, and beliefs over time. It is a complex process influenced by a range of factors, including:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Technological advances:</strong></span></p>
<p>Technological advances can drive social change by transforming the way people live and work. For example, the invention of the internet has transformed the way people communicate, access information, and conduct business.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Economic factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Economic factors such as globalization, industrialization, and changes in the job market can drive social change by altering the way people earn a living, their social status, and their standard of living.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Political factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Political factors such as changes in government policies and laws can drive social change by affecting people&#8217;s rights and freedoms. For example, the civil rights movement in the United States led to changes in laws that guaranteed equal rights for all citizens, regardless of race.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Cultural factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Cultural factors such as changes in values, beliefs, and social norms can drive social change by altering people&#8217;s attitudes and behaviors. For example, the women&#8217;s rights movement led to changes in social norms that encouraged gender equality and empowered women to pursue education and careers.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Environmental factors:</strong></span></p>
<p>Environmental factors such as climate change, natural disasters, and resource scarcity can drive social change by altering the way people live and interact with their environment.</p>
<p>Overall, social change is a complex and dynamic process that is influenced by a range of factors. By understanding these factors, we can better understand the causes and consequences of social change and work to create a more equitable and just society.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Why should we study computer ethics?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>We should study computer ethics for several reasons:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Protecting Privacy: In the age of big data, protecting privacy is crucial. Computer ethics ensures that personal information is protected from unauthorized access and use.</li>
<li>Preventing Cybercrime: Cybercrime is a growing threat to individuals, businesses, and governments. Computer ethics helps prevent cybercrime by promoting ethical behavior and responsible use of technology.</li>
<li>Ensuring Data Security: Data breaches can have serious consequences, including identity theft and financial losses. Computer ethics helps ensure that data is protected from unauthorized access and that appropriate security measures are in place.</li>
<li>Promoting Social Responsibility: Computer ethics promotes social responsibility by encouraging professionals in the field to consider the potential social and ethical implications of their work and take steps to mitigate any negative impacts.</li>
<li>Encouraging Professionalism: Computer ethics helps establish a set of professional standards and expectations for individuals working in the field of computer science and related professions. This encourages professionalism and ensures that professionals in the field are held to high ethical standards.</li>
<li>Preserving Intellectual Property: Intellectual property is a valuable asset that needs to be protected. Computer ethics promotes respect for intellectual property rights and helps prevent plagiarism, copyright infringement, and other forms of intellectual property theft.</li>
</ol>
<p>In summary, computer ethics is important because it helps protect privacy, prevent cybercrime, ensure data security, promote social responsibility, encourage professionalism, and preserve intellectual property. By promoting ethical behavior and responsible use of technology, computer ethics helps ensure that technology is used for the benefit of society.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Most copyright violations are found in developing, usually, poor countries. Why?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>There are several reasons why copyright violations are more common in developing countries, including:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Lack of awareness and education: Many people in developing countries may not be fully aware of copyright laws and their rights and obligations under them. This lack of understanding can lead to unintentional violations, as well as deliberate infringement by those who seek to profit from copying or distributing copyrighted works without permission.</li>
<li>Weak legal systems: In many developing countries, the legal systems may be weak or poorly enforced, making it easier for individuals and businesses to engage in copyright infringement without fear of significant consequences.</li>
<li>Economic factors: Developing countries may have lower levels of economic development and a greater prevalence of poverty, which can make it more difficult for individuals to access and afford legally acquired copyrighted works. As a result, people may resort to illegal means of obtaining or distributing copyrighted works.</li>
<li>Cultural norms: In some developing countries, there may be different cultural attitudes towards intellectual property and ownership. For example, some cultures may place greater emphasis on sharing and communal ownership, which may lead to a greater tolerance for copyright infringement.</li>
</ol>
<p>It is important to note, however, that copyright violations occur in all countries and are not limited to developing countries. Developed countries also face challenges in enforcing copyright laws and preventing infringement.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>How does ergonomics offer and maintain a safe, comfortable, healthy, and habitable work environment?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Ergonomics is the science of designing and arranging objects, equipment, and environments to fit the capabilities and limitations of the human body. By considering the physical, cognitive, and emotional needs of individuals, ergonomics can help create safe, comfortable, healthy, and habitable work environments.</p>
<p>Here are some ways in which ergonomics can offer and maintain such environments:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Reduce physical strain:</strong></span></p>
<p>Ergonomic design can help minimize physical strain on workers by ensuring that workstations and tools are properly sized, positioned, and adjusted. This can reduce the risk of musculoskeletal disorders, such as back pain and repetitive strain injuries.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Improve cognitive performance:</strong></span></p>
<p>Ergonomic design can also help improve cognitive performance by ensuring that work environments are free of distractions and clutter, and that information is presented in a clear and organized manner. This can improve worker productivity, accuracy, and decision-making.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Support emotional well-being:</strong></span></p>
<p>Ergonomic design can help support emotional well-being by creating work environments that are aesthetically pleasing, socially supportive, and psychologically comfortable. This can reduce stress, anxiety, and burnout, and promote job satisfaction and engagement.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Enhance safety:</strong></span></p>
<p>Ergonomic design can also enhance safety by reducing the risk of accidents and injuries, such as slips, falls, and collisions. This can be achieved by ensuring that work environments are well-lit, free of obstacles, and equipped with appropriate safety equipment.</p>
<p>Overall, ergonomics can help create work environments that are safe, comfortable, healthy, and habitable by taking into account the physical, cognitive, and emotional needs of workers. By doing so, ergonomics can improve worker well-being, performance, and satisfaction, and contribute to the overall success of organizations.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>What is a service level agreement (SLA)? Why it is important?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A service level agreement (SLA) is a contract or agreement between a service provider and a customer that specifies the level of service that will be provided. It outlines the quality and scope of services, the responsibilities of both parties, and the metrics by which performance will be measured.</p>
<p>SLAs are important for several reasons:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Performance Expectations:</strong></span></p>
<p>An SLA defines the expected level of performance for a service, which helps to manage expectations and ensure that customers receive a consistent level of service.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Accountability:</strong></span></p>
<p>An SLA outlines the responsibilities of both the service provider and the customer, providing a framework for accountability and ensuring that both parties are clear about their roles and obligations.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Transparency:</strong></span></p>
<p>An SLA provides transparency about the service provider&#8217;s performance, including metrics for measuring performance and penalties for failing to meet the agreed-upon service levels.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Dispute Resolution:</strong></span></p>
<p>An SLA provides a mechanism for resolving disputes between the service provider and the customer, helping to prevent disagreements and legal disputes.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Continuous Improvement:</strong></span></p>
<p>An SLA can be used to drive continuous improvement in the quality of service provided, by setting targets and identifying areas for improvement.</p>
<p>Overall, an SLA is an important tool for managing the relationship between a service provider and a customer, ensuring that both parties are clear about the expectations and responsibilities, and providing a framework for monitoring and improving service performance.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is risk assessment and management? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Risk assessment and management is the process of identifying, evaluating, and prioritizing potential risks that may impact an organization&#8217;s operations, assets, or objectives. It involves analyzing the likelihood and potential impact of risks and then implementing strategies to minimize or mitigate them.</p>
<p>The process of risk assessment and management typically involves the following steps:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Risk Identification:</strong> The first step is to identify potential risks that may affect the organization. This can be done through brainstorming sessions, risk registers, historical data analysis, or other methods.</li>
<li><strong>Risk Analysis:</strong> Once the risks are identified, they are analyzed to determine the likelihood and potential impact of each risk. This involves assessing the probability of the risk occurring and the severity of its impact on the organization.</li>
<li><strong>Risk Evaluation:</strong> After the risks are analyzed, they are evaluated to determine their significance and priority. This involves comparing the likelihood and potential impact of each risk against the organization&#8217;s risk appetite and tolerance.</li>
<li><strong>Risk Mitigation:</strong> Once the risks are evaluated, strategies are developed to mitigate or minimize the identified risks. This can include risk avoidance, risk transfer, risk reduction, or risk acceptance.</li>
<li><strong>Risk Monitoring and Review:</strong> The final step is to monitor and review the effectiveness of the risk management strategies implemented. This involves tracking the risks over time, identifying any new risks that may emerge, and revising the risk management plan as needed.</li>
</ol>
<p>Overall, risk assessment and management is a critical process that helps organizations proactively identify and mitigate potential risks, ensuring the continuity and success of their operations.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the benefits of computing virtualization? What is platform virtualization?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Computing virtualization refers to the process of creating a virtual version of an operating system, server, network, or other resources. There are several benefits of computing virtualization, including:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Cost Savings:</strong> Virtualization reduces hardware and infrastructure costs since multiple virtual machines can run on a single physical server, reducing the need for additional hardware.</li>
<li><strong>Improved Efficiency:</strong> Virtualization increases server utilization, reduces power consumption, and improves the overall efficiency of the IT infrastructure.</li>
<li><strong>Increased Flexibility:</strong> With virtualization, resources can be easily allocated, added, or removed as needed, allowing for greater flexibility and scalability.</li>
<li><strong>Enhanced Security:</strong> Virtualization allows for the isolation of applications and data, making it easier to manage and secure critical business data.</li>
<li><strong>Faster Disaster Recovery:</strong> Virtualization simplifies disaster recovery and reduces downtime since virtual machines can be easily backed up, replicated, and restored in the event of a disaster.</li>
<li><strong>Simplified Management:</strong> Virtualization makes it easier to manage IT infrastructure by consolidating resources, simplifying deployments, and reducing complexity.</li>
</ol>
<p>Overall, computing virtualization offers numerous benefits that can help organizations to reduce costs, increase efficiency, enhance security, and simplify the management of IT infrastructure.</p>
<p>Platform virtualization is a technology that enables multiple operating systems to run concurrently on a single physical server or computing device by creating virtual machines (VMs) that are isolated from each other and from the underlying physical hardware. It allows for efficient use of hardware resources, improves flexibility and scalability, and simplifies management of IT infrastructure.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>What is virtual reality? What are the different types of virtual reality?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Virtual reality (VR) refers to a computer-generated simulation of a 3D environment that can be experienced by a user through specialized hardware, such as a VR headset or goggles. VR technology creates a sense of presence and immersion, allowing users to interact with the virtual environment as if it were real.</p>
<p>There are several types of virtual reality, including:</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Fully immersive VR:</strong></span></p>
<p>This type of VR provides a completely immersive experience where the user is fully surrounded by a virtual environment. This is typically achieved through the use of a VR headset and controllers that allow users to interact with the environment.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Non-immersive VR:</strong></span></p>
<p>This type of VR provides a less immersive experience, where users interact with a virtual environment through a computer screen or projection. This can include 360-degree videos or simulations.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>c) Augmented reality (AR):</strong></span></p>
<p>AR technology overlays computer-generated graphics onto the real world, creating a mixed-reality experience. This can be achieved through the use of mobile devices or specialized AR glasses.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>d) Mixed reality (MR):</strong></span></p>
<p>MR combines elements of both VR and AR, allowing users to interact with both virtual and real-world objects in a seamless way. This type of VR is typically achieved through the use of specialized headsets and cameras that track the user&#8217;s movements and environment.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>e) Collaborative VR:</strong></span></p>
<p>This type of VR allows multiple users to interact with a shared virtual environment. This can be used for team collaboration, training, or social experiences.</p>
<p>Overall, virtual reality technology is constantly evolving, and there are many different types of VR that offer unique experiences and capabilities.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on:</p>
<ol>
<li>Cyberbullying</li>
<li>Globalization and migration</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>a) Cyberbullying:</strong></span></p>
<p>Cyberbullying refers to using electronic communication technologies, such as the internet, social media, text messages, and emails, to harass, humiliate, intimidate, or threaten someone. Cyberbullying can take various forms, including spreading rumors, posting embarrassing photos or videos, sending abusive messages, impersonating someone online, and excluding someone from online groups.</p>
<p>Some negative impacts of cyberbullying on victims include low self-esteem, depression, anxiety, suicidal thoughts, and even suicide attempts. Cyberbullying can also adversely affect the mental and physical health of the perpetrator and may lead to legal consequences.</p>
<p>Preventing cyberbullying requires a collaborative effort from parents, educators, and technology companies. Measures such as educating young people about responsible internet use, monitoring online activities, and implementing clear policies and consequences for cyberbullying can help to curb this harmful behavior. It is also essential to encourage victims to speak out and seek help if they experience cyberbullying.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>b) Globalization and migration:</strong></span></p>
<p>Globalization refers to the increasing interconnectedness of the world, characterized by the integration of markets, technologies, and cultures. It has led to the growth of international trade, investment, and the movement of people across borders.</p>
<p>Migration, on the other hand, refers to the movement of people from one place to another, either within their country or across international borders. It can be voluntary or forced and is driven by various factors such as economic opportunities, cultural exchange, conflicts, and environmental degradation.</p>
<p>Globalization and migration are interconnected, with globalization contributing to the increase in migration and migration, in turn, facilitating the exchange of ideas, cultures, and knowledge. However, they also present challenges such as social and cultural integration, national security, and human rights.</p>
<p>Overall, globalization and migration are complex and dynamic phenomena that have both positive and negative effects and require careful management to ensure that they benefit everyone and promote inclusive and sustainable development.</p>
</div>
